    "Unknown": "They passed by, in their march towards Jerusalem. Or, they passed away , i.e. departed without the success which they desired and confidently expected. [v_Psa_48_5]\n8. He mentions Judah only, and not all Israel; partly because they were more immediately and eminently concerned in Jerusalem\u2019s deliverance; and principally because ten of the tribes of Israel were now cut off from Jerusalem, and from the kingdom of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s house, and possibly carried away captive, 2Ki_18:9-",
    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "; see John `[char_John_Ref]` 7:5; Mark 3:31\u201335), and the insults that people threw at the Lord also fell on him (\nv. 8). This privilege is reserved for Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ (2:8; Zech. 9:9\u201310; Mic. 4:1\u20135; Luke 1:33). David `[char_David_Rut_4]` gained the kingdom through conquest and left it to his son, who strengthened it by means of treaties. His marriages to the daughters of neighboring kings were guarantees that these nations would cooperate with Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`\u2019s foreign policy. Even Sheba and the nomadic tribes in Arabia would pay tribute to Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`, and so would Seba in Upper Egypt; and kings as far away as Tarshish in Spain would submit to him. (See 1 Kings 4:21, 34; 10:14\u201315, 24\u201325; 2 Chron. 9:23\u201324.) But there is only one King of Kings, and that is Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ, the Son of God (Isa. 2:1\u20134; Dan. 7:13\u201314; Rev. 17:14; 19:16). There can be no peace on earth until the Prince of Peace is reigning and the nations have submitted to Him. A Compassionate Reign (vv. 12\u201314). The king of Israel was looked upon as God\u2019s shepherd who lovingly cared for God\u2019s flock (78:70\u201372; 100:3; Ezek. 34). Any citizen had access to the king to get help in solving legal problems, and the king was to make certain that the local judges were being fair and honest in their decisions. Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` didn\u2019t reach this ideal, for even though he had a vast bureaucracy, his officers didn\u2019t always aid the people (Eccl. 4:1). The picture here is surely that of our Savior, who had such great compassion for the needy and met their needs (Matt. 9:36). Not only does He hold their blood (life) precious to Him (",
    "Craig S. Keener": "Rost, Leonhard. 1976 Judaism outside the Hebrew Canon: An Introduction to the Documents. Translated by David `[char_David_Rut_4]` E. Green. Nashville: Abingdon Press. Rostovzeff, Mikhail I. 1957 The Social and Economic History of the Roman Empire. 2d ed. Oxford: Clarendon Press. Roth, Cecil. 1960a \"The Cleansing of the Temple and Zechariah xiv 21.\" Novum Testamentum 4: 174-81. 1960b \"The Subject Matter of Qumran Exegesis.\" Vetus Testamentum 10: 51-68. 1960c \"A Talmudic Reference to the Qumran Sect?\" Revue de Qumran 2: 261-",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "\u201cI will not UTTERLY DESTROY the house of Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`.\u201d All attempts to confine the prophecies to Israel alone (the northern tribes) will fall flat on their exegetical faces. Watching the expositors misapplying\nverses 1 and 9 in the passage and then watching them hit\n8. There is no deliverance in Mount Zion (vs. 17) in the NEB.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And Israel beheld Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`\u2019s sons, etc.] Ephraim and Manasseh, of whom he had been speaking as if they were absent, and he might not know until now that they were present, for his eyes were dim that he could not [v_Gen_49_10] see clearly, (<014910>Genesis 49:10); he saw two young men standing by Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, but knew not who they were, and therefore asked the following question: and said, who [are] these? whose sons are they? the Targum of Jonathan is, \u201cof whom were these born to thee?\u201d as if he knew them to be his sons, only inquired who the mother of them was; but the answer shows he knew them not to be his sons, and as for his wife, he could not be ignorant who she was.\nVer."
