    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`, in Galatians 1, is talking about the gospel of the grace of God. (Galatians 1 was written many years after Pentecost. When Galatians 1 was written, the gospel of the grace of God was so thoroughly established that even Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` was preaching it.) [v_Act_15_11] Acts 15:11\u2014\u201cBut we believe that through the grace of the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ we shall be saved, even as they.\u201d Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` has taught Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` this gospel, and he is preaching it. There isn\u2019t one cotton picking word about \u201cBUP tism\u201d in Acts\n1. Let\u2019s see you run to the Greek and get out of that one! The English will yield the true exposition. The gospel has four forms:\n1. We have the \u201cgospel of the grace of God.\u201d This is the good news in this age that God will save any sinner by grace who will simply trust him by faith; this is the good news of Romans 10 and [v_Rom_4_5] Romans 4:5, \u201cBut to him that worketh not, but believeth on him that justifieth the ungodly, his faith is counted for righteousness.\u201d",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And it came to pass after these things, etc.] Some little time after Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` had sent for Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, and conversed with him about his burial in the land of Canaan, and took an oath to bury him there, for then the time drew nigh that he must die: that [one] told Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, behold, thy father [is] sick; he was very infirm when he was last with him, and his natural strength decaying apace, by which he knew his end was near; but now he was seized with a sickness which threatened him with death speedily, and therefore very probably dispatched a messenger to acquaint Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` with it. Jarchi fancies that Ephraim, the son of Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, lived with Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` in the land of Goshen, and when he was sick went and told his father of it, but this is not likely from what follows: and he took with him his two sons, Manasseh and Ephraim; to see their grandfather before he died, to hear his dying words, and receive his blessing.\nVer.",
