    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "; 47:2; see Matt. 5:35). The greatness belongs to the Lord and not to the city (47:9), for in His grace, the Lord chose Zion (78:68; 132:13). The Jews saw Jerusalem as a beautiful city (50:2), a safe fortress, and \u201cthe joy of the whole earth\u201d (but see Lam. 2:15). Spiritually speaking, the city has brought joy to all the earth because outside its walls Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` died for the sins of the world, and from Jerusalem first sounded out the gospel of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. One day in the future, Jerusalem will be the center of Christ\u2019s glorious kingdom (Isa. 2:2ff.; 60:1ff.). Zaphon ( NIV ) refers to the north, a mountain in northern Syria where the god Baal was supposed to dwell. (See Ex. 14:2, 9; Num. 33:7.) The safety of Jerusalem was not in her location or her walls but in her God; for He was their fortress (\n2. God and Their Enemies (vv. 4\u20137). The citizens had been speaking about the Lord, but now they speak to the Lord about what He did to the Assyrians. Sennacherib and his huge army, plus the vassal kings of his empire (\n2. Vindication: \u201cJudge My Enemies!\u201d (vv. 19\u201329). David `[char_David_Rut_4]` told the Lord that his foes had dishonored and insulted him to the point that he was physically ill (vv. 19\u201321). When he looked for sympathy, none was to be found (Matt. 26:37), and his food and drink were unfit for human consumption (",
    "Craig S. Keener": "Edited by M. Philonenko et M. Simon. Paris: Librairie Orientaliste Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` Geuthner. 1992 \"La troisi\u00e8me demande du 'Notre P\u00e8re' et l'hymne de Nabuchodonosor.\" Revue d'Histoire et de Philosophie Religieuses 72: 23-31. 1993 \"Le sang du Juste (1 H\u00e9noch 47,1.4; Matthieu 27,24).\" Revue d'Histoire et de Philosophie Religieuses 73: 395-\n2. G\u00f6ttingen: Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht. Schmidt, Thomas Ewald. 1983 \"Hostility to Wealth in Philo of Alexandria.\" Journal for the Study of the New Testament 19: 85-97. 1988 \"Burden, Barrier, Blasphemy: Wealth [v_Mat_6_33] in Matt 6:33, Luke 14:33, and Luke16:15.\" Trinity Journal 9: 171-\n2. Rome: Biblical Institute Press. 1980 \"The Dharma of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`: An Interpretation of the Sermon on the Mount.\"Biblebhashyam 6: 358-81. (NTA 26:16) S\u00f6dig, Thomas. 1995 \"Feindeshass und Bruderliebe. Beobachtungen zur essenischen Ethik.\" Revue de Qumran 16: 601-",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "The reason why a Campbellite preacher can\u2019t face these problems is that basically, he has a mental problem. It\u2019s not that he\u2019s \u201cfull of the Devil\u201d or a \u201cheretic;\u201d it\u2019s just that he is a simpleton. When you get to Revelation 14, you have an angel preaching another gospel, and there isn\u2019t one mention of the \u201cnew birth,\u201d the \u201cresurrection,\u201d or the \u201ccrucifixion\u201d in the everlasting gospel! There is also no mention of baptism! [v_Rev_14_7] Revelation 14:7\u2014\u201cSaying with a loud voice, Fear God, and give glory to him; for the hour of his judgment is come....\u201d That\u2019s not the gospel of the grace of God! Does Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` mean in [v_Rev_14_7] Galatians 1 that this angel in Revelation 14:7 is cursed? Do you see the mess that a man can get into if he refuses to believe what he reads, as he reads it, where he finds it? For example: [v_Act_2_38] Acts 2:38\u201339\u2014\u201cThen Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` said unto them, Repent, and be baptized every one of you in the name of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ for the remission of sins, and ye [the house of Israel! Look at the context.] shall receive the gift of the Holy Ghost. For the promise is unto you [the house of Israel], and to your children [the house of Israel], and to all that are afar off, even as many as the Lord our God [the God of Israel\u2014Look at the context.] shall call.\u201d [v_Act_2_38] Alexander Campbell went around quoting Acts 2:38 as though it was the \u201cplan of salvation\u201d for a Gentile! What an insane thing! The context of the entire chapter is given to the house of Israel. \u201cYe men of Judaea, and all ye that dwell at Jerusalem\u201d [v_Act_2_14] (Acts 2:14). \u201cYe men of Israel, hear these words\u201d (Acts 2:22). \u201cTherefore let all the house of Israel know assuredly\u201d (Acts 2:36). The gospel in Acts 2 is not the gospel Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` is talking about in Galatians\n2. You cannot get them together unless you slight one of them, and Rome and the Campbellite church just kick Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` clean out, and take Simon Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`, the Book of Acts, and the Book of Matthew\u2014the earthly life and preaching of Christ. Of course, this is a distorted way of handling the Scripture. If all you preach and teach is the preaching and teaching of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ and the Apostles, you\u2019re nothing but a God forsaken, ecclesiastical wreck. Over three quarters of their preaching and teaching applies to Israel before the crucifixion or in the Tribulation! There\u2019s no truer statement ever written than the one from the Catholic book mentioned before, on page 11: \u201cHence it is that the Catholic does not say in the first instance \u2018What does the book say?\u2019 Rather he asks, \u2018What does the teaching church say?\u2019\u201d That is, an honest Catholic doesn\u2019t give a flip what the Book says. If the Book ever says one thing and the \u201cteaching church\u201d says something else, he\u2019ll burn that Bible as quick as look at it. Notice the wording: it doesn\u2019t say, \u201cWhat does the church say?\u201d, but, \u201cWhat does the teaching church say?\u201d Again, quoting from the book: \u201cThis fundamental vision of the church causes the Catholic to look to the episcopate for doctrine because the Roman Catholic bishops are the authentic exponents of God\u2019s message. This is no idolatry of the bishops or their primate, the Bishop of Rome, but it is only a consequence of the Catholic theory of the church.\u201d There you have the Catholic admitting that his entire authority is based on theory! (You\u2019ll find that statement printed \u201cwithout any objection\u201d by Francis Cardinal Spellman, the Archbishop of New York.) That\u2019s typical of Campbellite and Catholic interpretation. It is based on nothing but a subjective, hypothetical supposition that \u201cThe Church\u201d is their particular organization. Using that subjective bias as a framework for perverted exposition, these poor, depraved fanatics come to the word of God and force every verse to teach that their church is \u201cit.\u201d But every once in a while the Holy Spirit dumps a problem in their laps that they can\u2019t get out of, and this is one of them\u2014the angel in Revelation 14, and Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` in Acts 2, were not accursed, even though Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` said they would be in Galatians\n2. The gospel of the grace of God is also called \u201cmy gospel\u201d [v_Rom_2_16] by Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` in Romans 2:",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And [one] told Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, etc.] The same that came from Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` to Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` might be sent back by him to, his father, to let him know that he was coming to see him, or some other messenger sent on purpose; for it can hardly be thought that this was an accidental thing on either side: 800 and said, behold, thy son Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` cometh unto thee; to pay him a visit, and which no doubt gave him a pleasure, he being his beloved son, as well as he was great and honourable: and Israel strengthened himself, and sat upon his bed; his spirits revived, his strength renewed, he got fresh vigour on hearing his son Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` was coming; and he exerted all his strength, and raised himself up by the help of his staff, and sat upon his bed to receive his son\u2019s visit; for now it was when he blessed the sons of Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, that he leaned upon the top of his staff [v_Heb_11_21] and worshipped, as the apostle says, (<581121>Hebrews 11:21).\nVer."
