    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "). God speaks about the Jews (vv. 17\u201320). Once more Jeremiah used the image of the scattered flock. Assyria had ravaged Israel (the northern kingdom), and Babylon had ravaged Judah (the southern kingdom), but now God would punish Babylon as He had Assyria. (Assyria fell to a Babylonian-Median alliance in 609 BC.) God will bring His people back to their own land, where the flock may graze safely and peacefully. The prophet then looked down to the latter days when God will wipe away the nation\u2019s sins and establish His new covenant with them. We see the \u201ctwo horizons\u201d of prophecy again. God speaks to the invaders (vv. 21\u201327). The Lord was in command of the invasion, and His orders were to be carried out explicitly. Babylon the rod (Isa. 10:5 [c_Isa_10] [v_Isa_10_5] ) was itself shattered. Babylon was caught in God\u2019s trap and couldn\u2019t escape God\u2019s weapons. Their fine young men would be slaughtered like cattle, for the day of judgment for Babylon had come. The Jewish remnant speaks (",
