    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "You see, a Campbellite is unable to read the simplest passages. In Galatians 1 Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` said that an angel would be \u201caccursed\u201d if he preached \u201cany other gospel,\u201d but an angel did preach one, and so did Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`! They just preached them at different times. The poor Campbellite cannot \u201crightly divide the word.\u201d He doesn\u2019t know the times; he doesn\u2019t know the seasons; he doesn\u2019t know the dispensations; he doesn\u2019t study. All a Campbellite does is read debates and sermon outlines by Campbellite preachers to try to prove that if you don\u2019t join his church, he\u2019s a little better than you are because he\u2019s got enough sense to join \u201cthe real thing.\u201d All a Campbellite is, in the final analysis, is just a \u201cSouthern Catholic.\u201d There isn\u2019t a Catholic who ever lived that doesn\u2019t teach baptismal regeneration; there isn\u2019t a Catholic who ever lived that doesn\u2019t teach that his church is the one true church of Christ; there isn\u2019t a Catholic who ever lived that couldn\u2019t prove it just as quick as a Campbellite, if it came to a showdown and a test of strength. The only difference between a Catholic and a Campbellite is that a Catholic likes to be called a \u201cCatholic,\u201d and a Campbellite likes for folks to think that he is a \u201cChristian.\u201d In Acts 2, Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` preaches one gospel; in Galatians 1, Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` preaches another gospel; in Revelation 14, an angel preaches another gospel. This brings up a problem\u2014is the Bible a contradiction? NO! When Simon Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` preaches in Acts 2, he\u2019s preaching in A.D. 33. with no revelation but the Old Testament. When Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` preaches in 1 Corinthians 15 and Galatians 1, he has already received the revelation of the grace of God, which was ushered into this dispensation during the transition period in the Book of Acts. When Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` writes his epistles, late in the Book of Acts, he has been shown things that Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`, James, and John `[char_John_Ref]` knew absolutely nothing about. The Catholic and the Campbellite are both, in their ignorance, forever going back to a Jewish, circumcised minister, Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`, ministering to the Jews, in order to prove doctrines which are not even connected with the born again Christian Gentile. This is typical\u2014going to Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` instead of Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`! Notice the Roman Catholic teaching on this. This is from the Papal Encyclicals, and this is \u201cnihil obstat,\u201d by John `[char_John_Ref]` A. Goodwine, J.C.D., censor librarian, bearing the imprimatur of Francis Cardinal Spellman, Archbishop of New York. \u201cNihil obstat\u201d and \u201cimprimatur\u201d are official declarations that a book or pamphlet is free of doctrinal or moral error. This is the doctrinal statement from page 15: \u201cCatholicism insists that it teaches the preaching of Christ, and only that. The Catholic believes that his beliefs are identical with those of the Apostolic Church without a jot or tittle changed.\u201d This is typical of the Roman Catholic Church which rejected the entire doctrinal content of the Pauline Epistles. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` preaches to Israel, and Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` preaches to Gentiles; Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` preaches salvation by works in Matthew 24\u201325, and Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` preaches salvation by grace in Ephesians",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And he blessed Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, etc.] In his sons who were reckoned for him, and became the heads of tribes in his room: and said, God before whom my fathers Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` and Isaac did walk; in whom they believed, whom they professed, and whom they feared, served, and worshipped, and with whom they had communion: the God which fed me all my long unto this day; who had upheld him in life, provided for him all the necessaries of life, food and raiment, and had followed him with his goodness ever since he had a being, and had fed him as the great shepherd of the flock, both with temporal and spiritual food, being the God of his life, and of his mercies in every sense.\nVer."
